Trace (linear algebra)

In linear algebra, the trace of an "n"-by-"n" square matrix "A" is defined to be the sum of the elements on the main diagonal (the diagonal from the upper left to the lower right) of "A", i.e.,
where "ann" denotes the entry on the "n"-th row and "n"-th column of "A". The trace of a matrix is the sum of the (complex) eigenvalues, and it is invariant with respect to a change of basis. This characterization can be used to define the trace of a linear operator in general. Note that the trace is only defined for a square matrix (i.e., "n" Ã "n").
The trace is related to the derivative of the determinant (see Jacobi's formula).
The term trace is a calque from the German "Spur" (cognate with the English ""), which, as a function in mathematics, is often abbreviated to "tr".
