Phonology.
Consonants.
/n t d s z tÍ¡s dÍ¡z/ are denti-alveolar, while /l r/ are alveolar. The consonant sounds /f x/ are only found in loanwords. [Å] is only an allophone of nasals before velars /k/ and /g/. Latvian plosives are not aspirated (unlike in English). 
Voiced and unvoiced consonants assimilate to the next-standing consonant, e.g. apgabals [Ëabgabals] or labs [Ëlaps]. Voiced consonants don't get devoiced word-finally. At the same time single voiced consonants (d, t, z, g, dz etc.) don't get devoiced word-finally: "dzied" [ËdzieÌ¯d], "dedz" [dÃ¦dÍ¡z].
Doubled consonants are pronounced longer: "mamma" [ËmamËa]. Same with plosives and fricatives located between two short vowels: "upe" [ËupËe]. Same with 'zs' that is pronounced as /sË/, Å¡s and Å¾s as /ÊË/.
Palatalized dental trill /rÊ²/ is still used in some dialects (mainly outside Latvia) but quite rarely, and hence the corresponding letter "Å Å" was excluded from alphabet.
Vowels.
Latvian has six vowels, with length as distinctive feature:
/É ÉË/, and the diphthongs involving it other than /uÉ/, are confined to loanwords.
Vowel length ratio is about 1/2.5. Vowel length is phonemic and plays an important role in the language. For example "koka" [ËkuÉka] means 'made of wood', "kokÄ" [ËkuÉkaË] means 'on the tree'; "pile" [ËpilÉ] means 'a drop', and "pÄ«le" [ËpiËlÉ] means 'a duck'.
Latvian also has 10 diphthongs, four of which are only found in loanwords (/ai ui Éi au iÉ uÉ iu (Éi) Éu (Éu)/), although some diphthongs are mostly limited to proper names and interjections. Opening diphthongs are centred leading some sources to represent them as ending with /a/. If the second component of a diphthong is close, it is converted to a consonant when preceding a vowel, thereby /u/ and /i/ become [v] and [j].
Pitch accent.
Standard Latvian and, with a few minor exceptions, all of the Latvian dialects have fixed initial stress. Long vowels and diphthongs have a tone, regardless of their position in the word. This includes the so-called "mixed diphthongs", composed of a short vowel followed by a sonorant. There are three types of tones:
Some Latvian dialects have only two tones: in western parts of Latvia the falling tone merged with the broken tone, whereas in eastern parts of Latvia the level tone merged with the falling tone. Hence, the Central Latvian "traÅ©ks", "drÃ ugs", "raÃ»gs" corresponds to Western Latvian "traÅ©ks", "draÃ»gs", "raÃ»gs", and to Eastern Latvian "trÃ uks", "drÃ ugs", "raÃ»gs". Both the three-tone and the two-tone systems are accepted in standard Latvian. However, some dialects in Selonia also have the fourth (rising) tone.
This system is similar to the ones found in Lithuanian, Swedish, Norwegian, Limburgish and Serbo-Croatian. The broken tone is similar to that found in Danish stÃ¸d.

